{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Cues and psychological heuristics are not always reliable-they are 'shortcuts', and as such they can be suspected of impoverishing the gathering of evidence and inducing bias against candidates on inappropriate grounds, such as race or gender.",
    "However, some have argued that if cues are sufficiently varied, independent of each other, and reasonably reliable, they may enable uninformed voters to make decisions which are better than random-and thus enhance their \"epistemic performance\" (Goodin and Spiekermann 2018).",
    "Others have argued that political heuristics primarily enhance the decision-making of those who already have some expert knowledge of politics, i.e., competent voters (Lau and Redlawsk 2006).",
    "Competent voters are in a better position to interpret cues adequately.",
    "A single shortcutfor example, the party label 'Republican'-will have much more meaning and nuance in the mind of a political expert."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Others have argued that political heuristics primarily enhance the decision-making of those who already have some expert knowledge of politics, i.e., competent voters (Lau and Redlawsk 2006)."
  ]
}